\b historical visualization
\b0 \
\
I am working with Professor Lauren Klein and a Digital Media student to explore historical visualizations with modern technologies. One of our projects, about four months in duration, focused on William Playfair\'92s difference charts. We recreated this using d3.js to understand both the past and the present, how data is interpreted, and the idea of repair in digital media. This process resulted in two visualizations, one interactive and one static, and a paper which we submitted to Digital Humanities, a European-based conference. In particular, I worked on the static map and assisted in the writing of the paper. \
\
The biggest challenge I encountered while creating the static map was differentiating between existing data from William Playfair and data that I had to interpret. Ultimately I ended up using a technique described by Kevin Schaul. \
\
\pard\tx720\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\pardirnatural
\cf0 For a second project, we are making an educational technique from Elizabeth Peabody interactive using Javascript. Her idea is to show chronological events on a chart of 100 squares for a century, color-coded by country and placed by event type. This requires extensive custom Javascript code to make it modern and interactive. \
\
My main role in this project is to focus on the design and code for user interactions. I am particularly interested in how one might use and learn from this technique with modern technologies. A future idea I hope to pursue is developing the interactions for a physical rug, where a user might step or touch the square to interact with it and chart the history. This would involve extensive work with fabrication and Arduino. \
