\b0 \
\
\
brainstorm photo\
\
(intro)\
\
In a team of four, I went through an entire user-centered design cycle from identifying a problem to testing a prototype solution. To identify a problem space, I spoke with a friend who is a teacher to learn about her work and problems she regularly encounters. She described to me an issue that takes away from instruction time: fire drills. Frequent fire drills that schools are required to have take away from classroom time, and often take longer than they should be due to lack of communication between teachers and administrators. We initially decided to frame this problem from kindergarten to 12th grade, including not only fire drills but also intruder and severe weather drills. During the course of the semester, we narrowed it down to fire drills in high schools. Our reasoning was that high schools are the most chaotic environments - students are less likely to mind their teachers - and fire drills require the most movement of everyone. Solve the problem in this context, and the solution should easily extend to other, less complicated situation. \
\
My role: development of Axure prototypes, observation of fire drill and interviews with teachers/administrators, communication with participants for evaluation, leading brainstorm sessions, problem space identification\
\
\
(understand the problem space) \
\
Our first step was to understand more about the problem space. In addition to verifying that is is a problem for multiple teachers and schools, we wanted to know exactly who our potential users are, what tasks they might want to do, what our system should do, and what would make our system a success. To begin, we conducted semi-structured interviews with 10 people between the four of us. I spoke with three teachers. From these interviews, we learned that there is a communication gap between teachers and administrators which likely delays the return time to classrooms. In addition to speaking with our potential users, we also researched any existing commercial systems. We didn\'92t find any solution for our problem, but we did learn about emergency preparation plans. Based on our findings, we developed usability criteria to measure our future solution, as well as implications to guide our design development. \
\
img: task analysis\
\
(design alternatives) \
\
Together, we developed design alternatives. From our brainstorm session, we decided to sketch three ideas. In addition to a mobile app, we also explored a wearable jacket and a Google Glass app. At this point in time, we were able to visit a high school to observe a fire drill and speak with more teachers. Before the drill, we presented our sketches and wireframe mockups of our three ideas to a few teachers to get feedback. During the drill, we observed the teachers, students, and administrators, and took notes, especially on pain points. I was also able to speak with an administrator; because they are incredibly busy, an appointment couldn\'92t be scheduled, but he had some free time after the drill. Based on all of their feedback, plus feedback from a class poster session, we decided to prototype a mobile app. We made this decision due to a few reasons, such as the users\'92 familiarity with tech, flexibility, and cost. Phones are already used for communication, so this was a natural extension. \
\
